• Editor's note: This article was updated with new information. JOHANNESBURG - Former Prasa CEO Lucky Montana said the court judgment against the Swifambo Rail Holdings deal is flawed and must be challenged.  The South Gauteng High Court set aside Prasa's deal with Swifambo, labelling it corrupt. Montana was at the helm when the controversial contract was signed. READ: Fired Prasa boss Montana accuses Molefe of crimes He says the judge denied him an opportunity to present his argument, describing it as a travesty of justice. Montana's application -- to act as a friend of the court -- was dismissed. He believes the judgment is a massive blow to Prasa, and a major setback for its inter-city passenger rail project. Swifambo was ordered to pay back R2.6-billion to the rail agency, but the company plans to appeal the ruling. eNCA